⊢= observation-confluence
  ∴ Cell's confluence theorem states that independent cells can execute in
    any order with identical results. This program makes confluence concrete:
    two programs with different schedules (sum-first vs count-first) produce
    identical outputs (300, 10, 30). The proof traces the diamond pattern
    in the dependency graph and applies eval_diamond.

⊢= observation-crystallized-algebra
  ∴ All computation cells in both programs are crystallized (⊢=). This makes
    cell-wise equivalence trivial to verify — the ⊢= bodies are syntactically
    identical. Crystallization converts semantic equivalence (hard problem)
    into syntactic equivalence (easy problem).

⊢= observation-parallel-traces
  ∴ The two traces (trace-A, trace-B) are independent cells that could
    themselves execute in either order — meta-level confluence. The prover
    program itself exhibits the property it proves about its subjects.

⊢= observation-proof-carrying
  ∴ The equivalence certificate bundles: (1) two programs, (2) correspondence
    table, (3) execution traces, (4) formal proof with three steps,
